I’m really glad to see how close you are with your family. That picture of you standing behind your mom or grandmother—giving them rabbit ears with that big smile—made me laugh. It’s cute, and it shows how comfortable and connected you are with the people you love.

My own family is mostly in Minnesota. I have a younger brother who used to live in the Cities, but when his son went to college in Morris, he made the decision to move back to Alexandria so he could be closer to him, my sister, and my mom. He took a pay cut to do it, but he got four years of weekends with his son, Alex, while he was in school. That meant a lot to him.

My sister still lives in Alexandria too. She’s a hairstylist and has three daughters. The youngest, Tristan, is getting married. They recently threw her a bridal shower, and even though she’s pregnant, her doctor said it was fine for her to travel to Florida. She went with a big group of friends and had a great time. They spent their time on the beach. She’s in her twenties and really into tattoos—beautiful ones. So when I buy her gifts, I usually give her money to put toward her next tattoo. She’s slowly building out her sleeves. One of her tattoos is a dream catcher that matches her father’s, and she has a lot of animal designs because she loves animals.

My other two nieces, Keana and Christina, are twins, and they both have children. My sister absolutely loves being a grandmother. She and her husband live out in the country, and the kids love visiting. Her husband raises pigeons, so the grandkids help feed them. They also help in the garden, and in the summer they run around the huge lawn. It’s a good place for kids to grow up.

Recently my mom had some medical issues, and my brother and sister called me, so I took an emergency leave and flight back to Alexandria. We were all really worried, but she’s doing much better now. She’s in physical therapy and recovering well.

So I have one younger brother and one older sister. When I take vacations, I don’t go on cruises or anything like that—I just go home to Minnesota. The last time I visited, we went to St. Cloud, where one of my nieces lives. My sister loves Chinese food, so she always wants to go to the Chinese buffet. I like it too, but that time we tried a Thai restaurant, and I had this coconut curry chicken dish that was amazing. There are some great restaurants in that area.

You mentioned your dad asking whether I was strong or weak. I think strength isn’t about muscles or how tough you look. It’s about how you treat people and what you stand for. I was in the Navy and the Army—I even went through boot camp twice. After 9/11, I joined the Army and served with the 101st Screaming Eagles. I was deployed and earned a Combat Action Badge along with other military awards. But none of that is what I consider real strength.

Strength is standing up for your principles. Strength is caring for people. It’s coming home from deployment and crying when you see your family again. It’s getting up early to take your kids to school so your spouse can sleep in. It’s love, responsibility, and compassion—not how many push-ups you can do or how well you can fire an M16.

When I was stationed in the Philippines with Marines and SEALs, a lot of guys thought strength meant drinking until they were sick or getting into fights. That never made sense to me. My father was an alcohol so rarely drink.

When I worked in Chicago, sometimes the company would take us to baseball games. You haven’t lived until you’ve had a hot dog at a ballpark. I’m not a big sports guy, but the atmosphere is fun—music, fireworks, the whole experience.

We also used Groupon a lot back then—go-karts, bowling, all kinds of activities. And almost every Groupon deal came with pizza. But that’s Chicago for you.

When I lived in Nashville, I never tried Groupon, but I imagine the deals there would be more like horseback riding, BBQ, and country music.

